ngland":"Wantage, Berkshire, England","Waltham, Essex, England":"Waltham, Essex, England","Pattingham, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Pattingham, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","Pattingham, Staffordshire, England":"Pattingham, Staffordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Carter","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: occupational name for a transporter of goods, from Middle English <i>carter(e)</i> ‘carter’ (Anglo-Norman French <i>car(e)tier</i>, Old French <i>charetier</i>, medieval Latin <i>carettarius</i>, <i>carettator</i>). The Old French word coalesced with the earlier Middle English word <i>cart(e)</i> ‘cart’, which is from either Old Norse <i>kartr</i> or Old English <i>cræt</i>, both of which, like the Late Latin word, were probably derived from Celtic. This surname is also very common among African Americans.","Irish: shortened form of   McCarter  .","Americanized form of German   Karter   ‘carder’."],"variants":[{"name":"Charman","meanings":["English (Sussex and Surrey): occupational name for a carter, carrier, or coachman, from Middle English (Old French) <i>char</i>, <i>car</i> ‘car, cart, carriage’ + Middle English <i>man</i> ‘man’. Compare   Carter   and   Carman   2.","English (Sussex and Surrey): occupational name for someone who did odd jobs, from Middle English <i>char(re)</i>, <i>chere</i> (Old English <i>cier(r)</i>, <i>cer(r)</i>, <i>cear(r)</i>, <i>cær(r)</i>) ‘turn (of activity), small job, chore’ + <i>man</i>. Compare   Carman   2.","In some cases probably also an Americanized form of Slovenian <b>Čarman</b> (see   Carman   5)."]},{"name":"Chartier","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Armand, Normand, Jacques, Marcel, Adelard, Alcide, Emile, Gilles, Raoul, Rosaire, Alphonse.","French: shortened form of <i>charretier</i>, an occupational name for a carter, from an agent derivative of Old French <i>charette</i> ‘cart’.","French Canadian: altered form of English   Carter  , a cognate of 1 above. Compare   Sharkey   and   Shorkey  ."]},{"name":"Karter","meanings":["German: occupational name for a carder (someone who prepares wool for spinning), from Middle High German <i>karter</i>. Compare   Carter  ."]},{"name":"McCarter","meanings":["Scottish and northern Irish: variant of   McArthur  ."]},{"name":"Carrier","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Andre, Marcel, Emile, Lucien, Cecile, Alain, Gaetan, Gilles, Jacques, Laurent, Normand.","English and southern French: from Middle English, Old French <i>car(r)ier</i> (from Late Latin <i>carrarius</i>, a derivative of <i>carrum</i> ‘cart, wagon’, a word of Gaulish origin), an occupational name for a carter (see   Carter  ), in French also for a cartwright. Compare French   Charrier  .","French: occupational name for a stonemason or quarryman, <i>carrier</i>. Compare   Coyer  ."]},{"name":"Cartman","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Lancashire): occupational name from Middle English <i>cartman</i> ‘man who operated a cart for the transport of goods’. Compare   Carter  .","Americanized form of German <b>Kartmann</b> (see   Kartman  )."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When John Carter was born in 1535, his father, William Carter, was 25 and his mother, Mary Morrison, was 25. He married Annis Wedon on 7 May 1561, in Wantage, Berkshire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters. He died in 1573, at the age of 38."},"et":{"1535–1573":"1535–1573","1544–Female":"1544–Surnud","1565–1624":"1565–1624","1567–Female":"1567–Surnud","1510–1569":"1510–1569","1510–1572":"1510–1572","1569":"1569","1624":"1624","1535":"1535","1567":"1567","7 May 1561":"7. mai 1561","1544":"1544","1565":"1565","1510":"1510","about 1567":"umbes 1567",